N</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>'Understanding China' Visiting Scholar Fellowship</gtr:description><gtr:end>2016-08-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Confucius Institute</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>807E4214-1A50-49DD-B842-B63FFDD12ACA</gtr:id><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2016-08-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>ESRC directly funds two UK-based sub-projects, and so far we have the following findings:
The project on 'Muslim traders in China': The inflows of Muslim traders from the Middle East and Africa to China must be understood in their relation to the internal migration of Chinese Muslims. Local governments in Yiwu and Guangzhou in south China (re)built mosques and allowed for unregistered &amp;quot;prayer spots&amp;quot; in order to accommodate the need of foreign traders, who were important for the local economy. Migrant Chinese Muslims from the northwest utilised this policy stance to revive Islam, though they distinguished themselves from the foreign Muslims both religiously and culturally.

The project on 'Marriage migrations along China's border'. After two years of primary research we have discovered that marriage migration to China has extended in geographical scope and grown in numbers. Modalities of international and cross-border familial relations are more diverse than ever before. While in the past international marriage/cross-border relations were restricted to border areas or metropolitan centres, the phenomenon now concerns larger population with various profiles across rural and urban divides. International marriages pose a series of concerns to the Chinese authorities who face the challenge to adjust legal and administrative mechanisms to accommodate a growing number of foreign spouses, yet maintain the restrictive single citizenship regime. In the face of limited naturalisation prospects and denied access to labour market, foreign spouses on family visas turn to informal social networks and digital technologies to cope with social isolation, earn greater financial independence, or/and live their life beyond immediate Chinese family.

We have conducted two workshops in Asia (Taipei and Kyoto) for purposes of coordination, planning and information exchange. A meeting of the European partners will be held in April 2017 and a further meeting of all partners will be held in Shanghai (at our Chinese partner's institute) in August 2017 with the aim to coordinate, share and synthesise the ket findings of all partners involved.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>We are working on several publications based on our interim findings.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>C8486793-25A0-4EA4-9616-DF261A71AA28</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Creative Economy,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/648E6F51-8F6D-45C3-B014-9F796C314955"><gtr:id>648E6F51-8F6D-45C3-B014-9F796C314955</gtr:id><gtr:title>Chinese ENCOUNTERS in Southeast Asia</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/ebc683d036639206b1cb1c405adc7027"><gtr:id>ebc683d036639206b1cb1c405adc7027</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Grillot, C</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2016-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780295999302</gtr:isbn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/76E1D223-2F51-4ED4-A6DD-0D3F09F213C3"><gtr:id>76E1D223-2F51-4ED4-A6DD-0D3F09F213C3</gtr:id><gtr:title>&amp;quot;Trust facilitates business, but may also ruin it&amp;quot;: the hazardous facets of Sino-Vietnamese border trade</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Asian Anthropology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/b9fd5217123c993095f6c026d7c57994"><gtr:id>b9fd5217123c993095f6c026d7c5799